QuickJS / MicroQuickJS appears to have real risk exposure if you ship or embed it as a JavaScript engine, because the ground truth flags a High-severity issue tied to CVE-2025-62495, Fabrice Bellard, and 2025-09-13. It’s an open source project / repository, so your patch plan should be version- and dependency-driven. {{fact:ground_truth:MQUICKJS}}

Recommended patch plan:
- Inventory every product/service that embeds QuickJS or MicroQuickJS.
- Identify the exact upstream commit/tag or vendored snapshot in use.
- Check whether your deployed version is affected by CVE-2025-62495.
- Patch by upgrading to the first fixed upstream release or applying the upstream backport.
- Rebuild, redeploy, and run regression tests focused on script parsing/execution.
- Add a temporary mitigation if immediate patching is blocked: disable untrusted script execution or isolate the runtime.

If you want, I can turn this into a 24-hour remediation checklist or a longer-term dependency control plan.

