The literature anchor is the RyR2/calcium-leak axis in Alzheimer’s disease, with the strongest primary-source spine coming from PubMed-indexed work showing that post-translational remodeling of ryanodine receptors drives ER calcium leak and AD-like phenotypes, and that limiting RyR2 open time reduces neuronal hyperactivity and memory deficits in AD models {{cite:[2]|PubMed|type:source}} {{cite:[4]|PubMed|type:source}} {{cite:[5]|PubMed|type:source}}. A broader review also places calcium homeostasis, mitochondria, autophagy, and mitophagy early in the AD cascade {{cite:[3]|PubMed|type:source}}.

Methodologically, the solid parts are:
- Convergent evidence across genetics, pharmacology, and mouse models, not just one assay {{cite:[4]|PubMed|type:source}} {{cite:[5]|PubMed|type:source}}.
- Functional readouts: neuronal hyperactivity, memory/behavior, and calcium physiology, which are closer to mechanism than pure correlation {{cite:[4]|PubMed|type:source}} {{cite:[5]|PubMed|type:source}}.
- A mechanistic chain linking RyR2 dysregulation → calcium leak → downstream pathology, rather than only expression changes {{cite:[2]|PubMed|type:source}}.

Main caveat: much of the evidence is preclinical, so it supports mechanism and plausibility more than direct human causality.

