Where it’s weaker: the “agent” story can look like a feature layer rather than a durable new platform if customers believe the core value still lives in prompts, orchestration, and model choice. It also faces integration friction outside the Salesforce stack and may be vulnerable to more open, faster-moving agent platforms.

Three counter-positioning moves:
1. Position as the agent layer for heterogeneous enterprise systems, not just CRM.
2. Lead with autonomy + workflow reliability, not chatbot UX.
3. Win on developer control: faster iteration, easier composability, and lower lock-in.

The founder takeaway: don’t fight Salesforce head-on in CRM-centric deployments; attack the seams where customers want agents across many systems, with less vendor coupling and more control over behavior.

